    Introduction

    R6 class that creates b-splines.

    bspline.Rd

    Creates b-splines given some set of knot points, and then evaluates the splines given some set of coefficients for the splines. It has 3 arguments initialisation : f = BSpline(K, t_knot, m).

    Usage

    # S3 method for bspline
[(obj, t = NULL, n = NULL)

# S3 method for bspline
[(obj, t = NULL, n = NULL) <- value

    Arguments

    obj

    bspline object

    t

    points

    n

    number of derivatives

    value

    value

    Value

    b-splines

    Details

    Overloaded subscript operator

    Overloaded subscript operator assignment

    Public fields

    t_knot

    a Matrix. Spline knot points.

    K

    an integer. Order of polynomial.

    m

    a numeric. Spline coefficients (\(m = M \cdot D\)).

    B

    a numeric array with 3 dimension.

    x_mean

    a numeric. If set, these will be used to scale the output (default to 0).

    x_std

    a numeric. \(x_{out} = x_{std} \cdot (X \cdot m) + x_{mean}\)

    t_pp

    a numeric columnwise matrix. pp break points (size(t_pp) = nrow(t_knot) - 2*K + 1).

    C

    a vector. Piecewise polynomial coefficients (size(C) = [nrow(t_pp)-1, K]).

    Active bindings

    get_S

    Get \(S = K - 1\)

    get_domain

    Get the domain of t_knot

    Examples

    K <- 3 # order of spline
D <- K-1 # number of derivates to return
t <- Conj(t(matrix(0:10, nrow = 1))) # observation points

# increase the multiplicity of the end knots for higher order splines
t_knot <- rbind(
  array(t[1], dim = c(K-1, 1)),
  t,
  array(t[length(t)], dim = c(K-1, 1))
)

n_splines <- nrow(t) + K-2

# coefficients for the bsplines---set all of them to zero for now.
m <- array(0, dim = c(n_splines,1))

# initialize the BSpline class
B <- bspline$new(K = K, t_knot = t_knot, m = m)
